ies.com.au/my-account/\n015 National St, Corona New York, 11368',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 01:35:30','2021-02-25 01:35:30','National Pharmacies Inc','NY','PHARMACY'),(104,12,'https://www.walgreens.com/','No content','No content','60015','https://www.walgreens.com/findcare/vaccination/covid-19/location-screening\n\nWalgreen Co. 200 Wilmot Rd.MS #2002 Deerfield, IL 60015',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 01:45:33','2021-02-25 01:45:33','Walgreens Pharmacy','IL','PHARMACY'),(105,2,'https://local.pharmacy.tomthumb.com/\nhttps://www.tomthumb.com/pharmacy/covid-19.html','No content','No content','85038','M.S 10501 P.O Box 29093, Phoenix, AZ  85038',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 01:51:04','2021-02-25 01:51:27','Tom Thumb Pharmacy','AZ','PHARMACY'),(106,8,'https://www.krogerspecialtyinfusion.com/','No content','No content','32746','https://www.krogerspecialtyinfusion.com/covid-19\n3200 Lake Emma Road, Suite 1000 Lake Mary, FL 32746 United States',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 01:53:16','2021-02-25 01:54:06','Kroger Specialty Infusion','FL','PHARMACY'),(107,43,'https://intermountainhealthcare.org/locations/location-details/salt-lake-clinic/intermountain-pharmacy-salt-lake-clinic/?utm_campaign=gmb-website&utm_medium=organic&utm_source=google','No content','No content','84102','389 S 900 E Salt Lake City, UT 84102',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 01:56:09','2021-02-25 01:56:45','Intermountain Pharmacy - Salt Lake Clinic','UT','PHARMACY'),(108,31,'https://covid19vaccine.health.ny.gov/','Get the Facts\nThe COVID-19 Vaccine Is Here!\nThe first COVID-19 vaccines are here. Supply from the Federal Government is extremely limited. Additional New Yorkers will become eligible as the vaccine supply increases. While the vaccination process is underway, every New Yorker should wear a mask, social distance and avoid small and large gatherings.\nOver seven million New Yorkers are now eligible for the vaccine. Eligible groups include doctors, nurses and health care workers, people age 65 and over, first responders, teachers, public transit workers, grocery store workers and public safety workers. \nBeginning February 15, New Yorkers with certain comorbidities and underlying conditions will be eligible to receive the vaccine.\nVaccines are available at pharmacies, hospitals and through local health departments statewide – please contact your provider of choice to schedule your vaccine appointment. You can use this website for scheduling a first-dose appointment at a New York State-run site only. To determine eligibility and schedule a first-dose appointment at one of these sites, use the Am I Eligible app. Remember: Both vaccines require two doses for effectiveness. Your second-dose appointment will be scheduled automatically at the time you receive your first vaccine dose. Appointments are not transferrable.\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccine Tracker\n\nInstructions for New York State-Operated Vaccination Sites:\nStep 1: Determine eligibility and schedule an appointment. The Am I Eligible app is the quickest way to see if youre eligible and make an appointment. You can also call the New York State COVID-19 Vaccination Hotline at 1-833-NYS-4-VAX (1-833-697-4829). Once you have successfully scheduled an appointment, you will receive a confirmation email that contains a barcode. You will need to bring this to your appointment.\nStep 2: Complete the Vaccine Form. Once you have a confirmed appointment, you must complete the New York State COVID-19 Vaccine Form. This form should be filled out online and you will receive a submission ID indicating completion. You will need to bring the submission ID to your appointment. If you cannot submit the form online, it will be available at the vaccination sites.\nStep 3: Bring proof of eligibility to your appointment. Depending on your eligibility category, proof can include an employee ID card, a letter from an employer or affiliated organization, a pay stub, a drivers license, passport, or any legal proof of your date of birth and residency. At the time of your appointment, youll be asked a series of clinical questions to ensure readiness for a vaccine. You will be asked for insurance information BUT the vaccine is free and there will never be a charge to you. This information is for administrative use only.\nStep 4: Your second dose appointment will be scheduled automatically when you receive your first vaccine dose. Your second appointment will be scheduled for the same time and at the same location, three weeks following your first dose. You will receive a card onsite with the date and time indicated and a confirmation email will follow a few days later. Please keep in mind when scheduling your first appointment that your second appointment will occur at the same time of day.\n\n\nX\n\n \nGET DAILY COVID-19 AND VACCINE UPDATES\nSign up here','No content','10013','-',1,NULL,'2021-02-25 15:20:33','2021-02-26 08:56:33','New York State','NY','div|paragraph paragraph--type--webny-wysiwyg-pgtype paragraph--view-mode--default'),(109,43,'https://www.shrinershospitalsforchildren.org/salt-lake-city','At Shriners Hospitals for Children, the health and safety of our patients, families, volunteers and staff is our top priority. With the evolving situation regarding COVID-19, we are closely monitoring updates from local health departments and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), and are actively following their recommendations.\nIf your child has an upcoming appointment, please contact your local Shriners Hospitals for Children location.\n\nWhat to expect at Shriners Hospitals for Children — Salt Lake City.','No content','84103','1275 E. Fairfax Rd. Salt Lake City, UT 84103',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 07:43:08','2021-02-26 07:43:08','Shriners Hospitals for Children - Salt Lake City','UT','div|splash-wrap'),(110,4,'http://www.buttecounty.net/ph/COVID19/vaccine','Federal Retail Pharmacy Program:\nCVS Pharmacy | 260 Spruce St., in Gridley\nCOVID-19 Vaccinations available by appointment only. CVS will vaccinate individuals who are currently eligible to receive COVID-19 vaccine in Butte County, including persons 65+ and healthcare workers. Open seven days a week.\n\nBook a vaccination appointment at CVS in Gridley:\nOnline at: www.cvs.com\nBy phone at: 800-746-7287.   \n\nFirst Dose Community Vaccination Clinics\nThere are currently no first dose community vaccination clinics scheduled. First Dose clinics will be scheduled based on vaccine supply and allocations for Butte County.','No content','95914','-',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 09:01:41','2021-02-26 09:01:41','Butte County','CA','div|dnn_ctr11651_HtmlModule_lblContent'),(111,31,'https://nyulangone.org/locations/covid-19-vaccine','NYU Langone is offering the coronavirus disease (COVID-19) vaccine to eligible patients, based on guidelines from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the New York State Department of Health—as well as our available supply of the vaccine, which has been limited.To learn more about the COVID-19 vaccine and vaccine safety, read our COVID-19 vaccine information for patients.COVID-19 Vaccination Appointments at NYU LangoneWe are notifying each of our patients individually when you can schedule your vaccination. This is based on both your eligibility as determined by New York State and our available supply. The New York State Department of Health is currently prioritizing vaccine distribution to public vaccine clinics, so our vaccine supply for patients is limited.You will be notified that you are able to schedule by email or text message based on the contact information in your NYU Langone Health MyChart account. Please make sure your contact information is up to date. If you are an NYU Langone patient and do not have a MyChart account, create your account now so you can schedule your appointment as soon as you receive a notification.You can also download the NYU Langone Health app, so you can quickly and easily schedule your vaccination appointment when eligible.NYU Langone Health AppSchedule your COVID-19 vaccination when eligible, access your medical records, and more by logging into the NYU Langone Health app with your MyChart account.Download NowPlease do not call your doctor’s office about scheduling your vaccination appointment, as our vaccination appointments are made at specialized vaccination sites in Manhattan, Brooklyn, and Queens and on Long Island. You will be able to choose the location and time that is most convenient for you.To ensure that the vaccine is available for your appointment, we are scheduling vaccinations only after we have confirmed that we have doses available for distribution. This is done to make sure we do not have to cancel vaccination appointments after they have been scheduled.Important Vaccine Information and ConsiderationsWhen we notify you that you are eligible to schedule your vaccination, we encourage you to schedule your appointment as soon as possible, as availability is limited. We receive different COVID-19 vaccines from different companies. You will not be able to choose the vaccine you receive, and we will not be able to tell you the vaccine in advance.Most people can immediately schedule after you receive the MyChart or text notification. However, we ask that you first contact your doctor before making an appointment if any of these categories apply to you:You had a severe allergic reaction to a vaccine in the past.You are pregnant, thinking of becoming pregnant, or breastfeeding.You have a condition that affects your immune system.You are getting radiation therapy or chemotherapy.You are taking medications that affect your immune system or have taken corticosteroids for more than 14 days.Please do not schedule a vaccination or come to NYU Langone to be vaccinated if any of the following statements apply to you:You received your first dose of the vaccine somewhere else. Please schedule your second dose at the same location you received your first dose.You are currently feeling sick.You have an active COVID-19 infection. You can schedule 10 days after you have received a positive COVID-19 test result or 72 hours after your fever ends.You received a COVID-19 diagnosis and were treated with COVID-19 monoclonal antibody infusions or convalescent plasma within the past 90 days.You have had any vaccine in the past 14 days.After you complete your first vaccination, you will need to schedule your second vaccination through MyChart. You will be able to schedule the second vaccination between three and four weeks after your first dose, depending on the vaccine you received.Understanding the COVID-19 VaccineThe CDC provides detailed information about the COVID-19 vaccine, and NYU Langone also provides vaccine information for patients.If you have specific questions about the vaccine related to your health, please contact your NYU Langone provider.','No content','11201','83 Amity St Corner of Amity and Hicks Streets Brooklyn, NY 11201',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 11:30:12','2021-02-26 11:36:09','Emergency Department at NYU Langone Health - Cobble Hill','NY','div|section__columns'),(112,20,'https://newhealthcenter.org/covid-vaccination-info/','COVID Vaccination Info','No content','02113','332 Hanover St, Boston, MA 02113, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:39:13','2021-02-27 03:33:54','North End Waterfront Health','MA','div|col-md-12'),(113,20,'https://www.bu.edu/president/vaccine-distribution-at-boston-university/','No content','No content','02215','881 Commonwealth Avenue, Boston, MA 02215, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:40:27','2021-02-27 04:24:40','Boston University Student Health Services - Primary Care','MA','div|post-1484 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-letters'),(114,20,'https://coronavirus.bilh.org/vaccine/?utm_source=bidmc&utm_medium=referral&utm_campaign=vaccine2021&utm_content=alert-vaccine','No content','No content','02150','1000 Broadway, Chelsea, MA 02150, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:42:38','2021-02-27 04:26:38','Beth Israel Deaconess HealthCare-Chelsea - Internal Medicine','MA','div|subtitle'),(116,12,'https://www.amitahealth.org/covid-19/vaccine','In accordance with public health guidelines, we are reaching out initially to eligible AMITA Health patients to schedule vaccine appointments when they are available. COVID-19 vaccine supply is very limited at this time. Please check back regularly for vaccine updates.\nAdditionally, if you reside in any of the following counties, you may wish to register for information on when vaccine may be available through your county.\n\nCook County\nDuPage County\nKane County\nKankakee County\nLake County\nMcHenry County\nWill County (alternative link)\n\n\n\n\nAMITA Healths Vaccination Plan\nAMITA Health is following public health guidelines regarding the distribution and administration of vaccines. The following populations in the state of Illinois are currently eligible to receive vaccines:\n\n\n\nPhase\nPopulation Group\nCan I Receive My Vaccine?\n\n\n1a\nHealthcare personnelLong-term care facility residents\nYes\n\n\n1b\nAnyone aged 65 or olderFirst respondersFrontline essential workers (education & childcare, food & agriculture, postal service, grocery stores, public transit, manufacturing, correctional facilities, shelters & adult day care)\nYes\n\n\n\n\nNOTE: Cook County and Lake County residents not included in this expansionIllinois residents ages 16–64 with the following high-risk comorbid conditions:\n\nCancer\nChronic kidney disease\nChronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\nDiabetes\nHeart condition\nImmunocompromised state from a solid organ transplant\nObesity\nPregnancy\nPulmonary disease\nSickle cell disease\n\n\nYes\n\n\n1c\nPeople ages 16–64 with the above high-risk comorbid conditionsOther essential workers (transportation & logistics, food service, construction, information technology, public health, etc.)\nNo(Estimated Start Date TBD)\n\n\n2\nEveryone (age 16 or older)\nNo(Estimated Start Date TBD)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWe Got The Vaccine. Heres Why.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\"COVID-19 is disproportionately ravaging minority communities, so it is incumbent upon us to step up and get vaccinated.\"\nRichard Phillips, MDMedical Director, Emergency Department\n\n\n\n\n\n\"I am pregnant… I had a chance to protect myself, my baby and everyone around me.\"\nBernadette Pabalate, RN, BSNAssistant Patient Care Manager\n\n\n\n\n\n\"After fighting COVID-19 for 10 months, I wanted to protect myself and others, and help our community rebuild.\"\nNishi Sahgal, MDInfectious Disease Specialist\n\n\n\n\n\n\"After seeing how sick people can get from COVID-19, I felt the vaccine was the only way to make a large impact in the fight against the pandemic.\"\nDaniel Haslett, MSN, RNEmergency Department Manager\n\n\n\n\n\n\"I reviewed the research and felt comfortable getting it. I felt blessed to receive it, and I felt like a part of history.\"\nMary Murphy, RN, MSNRegional Chief Nursing Officer\n\n\n\n\n\n\"I got vaccinated for me, my family, my team, my patients and, most important, my society.\"\nMorgan Cottrell, BSNNursing Director, Critical Care Services\n\n\n\n\n\n\"Being vaccinated gave me peace of mind, and I felt less stressed at work.\"\nCherryl UngosPhlebotomy Supervisor\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nFrequently Asked Questions\n\n\n\n\n\nHow does the vaccine work?  \n\n\n\nAll vaccines use your immune systems natural processes to \"teach\" your body to recognize and fight new diseases without exposing you to the disease itself. Typically, they use dead or weakened parts of the disease, known as antigens, to trick your immune system into thinking there’s an intruder in your body. Your cells then create antibodies to fight and destroy the antigen. Because your body will remember how to make these antibodies, it will be ready to react if you are exposed to the live virus.\nBoth COVID-19 vaccines use an innovative new approach. Instead of using dead or weakened antigens, the vaccine introduces your body to COVID-19s messenger ribonucleic acid (mRNA). In response, your cells make a piece of a protein that is found on the surface of the COVID-19 virus. Because your body does not recognize this protein, it will immediately begin making antibodies to destroy it. Your immune system will then remember how to fight the COVID-19 virus if you are exposed to it later.\n\n\n\n \n\n\nDoes it matter which vaccine I get?  \n\n\n\nBoth the Pfizer/BioNTech and the Moderna vaccines are equally effective (about 95% effective), so it doesn’t matter which one you get. But the vaccines are NOT interchangeable. So your first and second doses will need to be made by the same company. The two vaccines also have slightly different intervals between doses (21 days for Pfizer/BioNTech and 28 days for Moderna).\n\n\n\n\n\n\nHow strict is the recommended time between doses?  \n\n\n\nThe recommended interval for both vaccines should be followed whenever possible:\n\nPfizer/BioNTech: 21 days\nModerna: 28 days\n\n\nThat said, researchers at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention say you can receive your second dose up to four days early. AMITA Health’s experts encourage you to receive your second dose no later than four days after the recommended interval.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCan a vaccine that was created this quickly be safe?  \n\n\n\nGiven the widespread impact on health and safety, medical and research scientists worldwide have placed unprecedented collaborative focus on developing a COVID-19 vaccine. While this vaccine is available faster than what is typical, the COVID-19 vaccine has been approved by the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for emergency use authorization, and has passed clinical trials and rigorous testing to help ensure that it is both effective and safe.\n\n\n\n \n\n\nDo AMITA Healths medical experts think the vaccine is safe?  \n\n\n\nAMITA Health is committed to the health and safety of all patients, visitors, community and staff. Our physicians support the FDAs efforts and believe that the COVID-19 vaccine is safe.\n\n\n\n \n\n\nWhat are the risks of the vaccine?  \n\n\n\nThe FDAs rigorous testing helps ensure that vaccines are safe. However, all medications (including vaccines) carry a low risk of side effects. Most common side effects are identified in clinical trials before the vaccine is approved, but less common side effects may not be detected until the medicines or vaccines are more widely available. Thats why vaccines are continuously, carefully monitored for possible side effects even after they are approved.\nThe most common reported side effects of the COVID-19 vaccine include pain and swelling on the arm where you receive the vaccine. Some recipients have also experienced mild fever, chills, fatigue and headache.\nIf you experience side effects after your vaccination, please bear in mind that this is normal. It means your immune system is working properly. These side effects should go away in a few days. Contact your healthcare provider if your side effects increase or do not go away after a few days.\n\n\n\n \n\n\nCan I get vaccinated if I’ve already had COVID-19?  \n\n\n\nYou can and you should. Research shows it’s rare for people who have had COVID-19 to get reinfected within 90 days, but you would not need to wait 90 days for your vaccination:\n\nIf you’ve had COVID-19 with symptoms, you can get the vaccine once you no longer have symptoms\nIf you were asymptomatic, you can get the vaccine 10 days after a positive PCR test\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\nCan I get vaccinated if I’m pregnant or breastfeeding?  \n\n\n\nYes, according to researchers at the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG). A pregnant woman can pass immunity on to her baby. However, a conversation with your doctor beforehand might be helpful if you are pregnant or planning to get pregnant.\n\n\n\n \n\n\nIf I receive the vaccine, can I stop wearing a mask and social distancing?  \n\n\n\nNo, continued use of a mask, social distancing and washing your hands frequently is highly recommended until the vaccine is received by the majority of the community.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nDoes the flu vaccine cover COVID-19, too?  \n\n\n\nNo. The flu vaccine is important to protect you from influenza, particularly during the current coronavirus pandemic, but it does not vaccinate you from COVID-19. Receiving a vaccine is important to stay healthy.\n\n\n\n\n\n\nI got the flu vaccine and still got the flu. How do we know the COVID-19 vaccine is effective?  \n\n\n\nAnnual flu vaccines are challenging because the strains of influenza virus that are prevalent change each year. In addition, there is a two-week period for the vaccine to reach its full effect. In some cases, getting a vaccine does not prevent illness, but for most people, it does. This is why the seasonal flu vaccine’s effectiveness is between 40–60%, according to the CDC.\nCompare this to the two COVID-19 vaccines that have received FDA emergency use authorization, which appear to be about 95% effective in preventing the infection. Moreover, early data from Public Health Englands SIREN Study suggests that even a single dose can reduce the risk of infection by more than 75% and interrupt viral transmission. Vaccinated people who do get infected are far less likely to die or be hospitalized; early data shows a reduction of more than 75%.\n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Prevention & Wellness\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Variants: What Everyone Should Know\nVariants of the novel coronavirus have come to the U.S. Learn about what these variants do — and what you can do first.\nLearn More\n\n\n\n\nWhat to Do While You Wait for the COVID-19 Vaccine\nAs you wait for your turn to get the COVID-19 vaccine, dont lose sight of your physical, mental and emotional health.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Holiday Safety Tips\nMay your days be merry and bright with our medical expert’s advice for celebrating the season safely.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\n\"COVID Fatigue\" and How to Fight It\nEmotional fatigue caused by COVID-19 is real and affects us all. Our therapist shares the strategies she uses to cope with her own fatigue.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nIs It a Cold, the Flu or COVID-19?\nWe’re entering a perfect storm of flu season, head colds and COVID-19 spikes. Stay calm (and safe) by understanding your symptoms.\nCheck Your Symptoms\n\n\n\n\nHow to Sleep When the World Is a Mess\nHow do you sleep when you can’t stop thinking about COVID-19 and the state of the world? Sleep well even when stressed with these 7 tactics.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nObesity and COVID-19: What You Need to Know\nYour weight can raise your risk of severe illness from COVID-19. Find out if you’re affected and what you can do to protect yourself.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nGetting Over the Emotional Trauma of COVID-19\nAs the state reopens, is your state of mind still on lockdown? Begin your recovery from COVID-19 trauma with our PTSD expert’s help.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nHow Our Mental Health Providers Cope with Stress\nNature, cooking, dungeons, dragons — AMITA Health’s counselors and therapists share their personal strategies for coping with stress and anxiety.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nAre You Reading Your Childs Nonverbal Cues Right?\nChildren communicate a lot about how they feel with nonverbal gestures and behaviors. Learn to read those cues like an expert (and spot serious red flags).\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nAre You Slipping into Unhealthy Habits?\nStress levels are up. So are alcohol sales, porn traffic and video game usage. At what point does a habit become a problem?\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nHow to Boost Your Core Strength at Home\nThe stronger your core muscles, the lower your risk of an injury this summer. Our physical therapists recommend these at-home exercises.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nHow Do Our Dietitians Stay Healthy at Home?\nUnhealthy habits can happen to the best of us, especially now. Our expert dietitians share their personal strategies for success.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\n3 Easy Ways to Stop Overthinking\nAn AMITA Health anxiety expert shows you how to stop overthinking and ruminating on negative thoughts with 3 exercises you can do right now.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nGet an Immune System of Steel with These 3 Foods\nEating 3 natural immunity boosters — and avoiding 3 \"immunity bullies\" — can help your family stave off inflammation and disease.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nHow to Grieve While Social Distancing\nHow do you mourn when you can’t be there for the memorial? Map a new path to closure with advice from AMITA Health’s grief counselors.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nHow to Exercise at Home with Your Kids\nMake your at-home workout fun by involving your baby, kids or teens in these exercises recommended by AMITA Health’s physical therapists.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nJuggling the Demands of Working from Home\nSheltering in place blurs the line between work and home life. Find the balance and manage your stress levels with these simple strategies.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nLow-Carb Lockdown: Setting Up Your Kitchen for Success\nSheltering in place got you stressing (and stress-eating)? Curb mindless munching with five simple strategies from a registered dietitian.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nMake Your Home Office Ergo-Friendly\nIs COVID-19 forcing you to work from home? Turn your workspace into an ergonomic oasis with a little help from our physical therapists.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\nManaging Your COVID-19 Anxiety\nOur lead clinical psychologist shares 9 techniques for coping with stress and anxiety in this new era of quarantines and social distancing.\nRead Article\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nAdditional Resources\nBecause of how important the vaccine is, people are sharing information about it through social media and other channels. Unfortunately, they might be passing along misinformation as well, either knowingly or unknowingly. When in doubt, we recommend consulting these credible and trustworthy sources:\n\nCenters for Disease & Control Prevention (CDC)\nIllinois Department of Public Health\n\nCook County\n\nChicago\n\nDuPage County\nKane County\nKankakee County\nLake County\nMcHenry County\nWill County\n\nAMITA Health COVID-19 Resource Center\n\nTop 10 COVID-19 Vaccine Myths Busted','No content','60657','2900 N Lake Shore Dr, Chicago, IL 60657, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:44:07','2021-02-27 04:31:19','AMITA Health Saint Joseph Hospital Chicago','IL','div|col-xs-12 ih-content-column'),(117,12,'https://www.sinaichicago.org/en/covid-19/vaccine-request/','No content','No content','60608','1500 S Fairfield Ave, Chicago, IL 60608, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:44:57','2021-02-27 04:36:33','Mount Sinai Hospital','IL','div|container'),(118,12,'https://vaccine.cookcountyil.gov/','No content','No content','60615','500 E 51st St, Chicago, IL 60615, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:45:51','2021-02-27 04:40:25','Provident Hospital of Cook County','IL','div|root'),(119,12,'https://www.uchicagomedicine.org/patients-visitors/patient-information/coronavirus-information/covid-19-vaccine','Patient registration for the COVID-19 vaccine is not available at this time. When we are able to vaccinate patients, vaccines will be offered to a limited number of eligible patients through a lottery. Lottery enrollment is automatic. You do not need to take action to be added to the pool and do not need to call us to confirm your eligibility. You will get a message through MyChart, texts, and/or a telephone call when the lottery determines it is your turn to schedule a vaccination appointment.\nCOVID-19 vaccines are safe, effective and the fastest way to bring an end to this global pandemic. We understand you may have questions, and we will do our best to provide you with information and updates as we learn more about the vaccine’s rollout to our patients and the South Side community. Here is what you need to know about the COVID-19 vaccination program for UChicago Medicine patients:\n\nPublic health agencies have granted us permission to provide COVID-19 vaccines to limited groups of people. We must follow their instructions. At our main hospital in Hyde Park, we are now allowed to vaccinate:\n    \nCurrent patients who are 65 years and older.\nHealthcare workers, including some unaffiliated frontline healthcare workers. (Space may be limited.)\n\n\nWe are using a lottery to vaccinate current patients who have been prioritized by public health agencies. Enrollment in the lottery is automatic, and registration is not available. You do not need to take any action to be added to the pool. If you are randomly selected for the vaccine, you will get a message through MyChart and telephone calls when it is your turn to get a vaccine. You will get instructions explaining how to schedule your appointment at that time.\nUChicago Medicine Ingalls Memorial has not yet begun patient vaccination. Additional information will be provided as that vaccination effort begins\nWe will share updates once we are authorized by public health agencies to vaccinate larger groups of patients. Contact your local public health department for alternative vaccine locations if you are not currently eligible to receive a vaccine through our patient program. Learn more about the Chicago Department of Public Health (CDPH) distribution or access the Illinois Department of Public Healths vaccine finder.\nIf you need to see your doctor for any other reason, we are ready to serve you. Please call to schedule an in-person or video visit appointment as you normally would.\nPlease continue to stay safe and healthy by practicing social distancing, wearing a face covering and washing your hands. If you don’t feel well, stay home and request a COVID-19 test through MyChart or by calling 773-702-2800.\n\n \n\nCOVID-19 Vaccination Registration and Scheduling FAQs for UChicago Medicine Patients\n\n\n\n\nWhen will UChicago Medicine distribute the COVID-19 vaccine to patients?\n\n\n\n\n\n\nUChicago Medicine is vaccinating patients as we get authorization to do so from the Chicago Department of Public Health (CDPH). Patients who are eligible to receive vaccines will be automatically entered into a lottery that follows public health guidelines. Patients do not need to take action to be added to the pool and will be notified though MyChart messages, texts, and/or phone calls if and when it is their turn to schedule a vaccine.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWhen will I know if I can get a COVID-19 vaccine from UChicago Medicine?\n\n\n\n\n\n\nUChicago Medicine will contact patients as we learn more about distribution plans and determine when we can begin to broadly vaccinate patients. You also can check this webpage for updates. When patients are eligible for a vaccine through our automatic lottery, they will get a message through MyChart, texts, and/or a telephone call when it is their turn. Lottery enrollment is automatic, and patients will not need to take action to be added to the pool.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWho will be able to get vaccinated first from UChicago Medicine?\n\n\n\n\n\n\nInitially, we will invite current patients who are 75 and older and who live within the South Side’s 15 ZIP codes we serve to be vaccinated. After that, we will expand to those who are 65 and older and are from the same communities. Then we will expand further into the greater Chicagoland area. In all phases, we will use a lottery. We will continue to provide the vaccine in an efficient and orderly manner and are committed to using all doses provided to us. This initial distribution process, which may be revised, was developed in consultation with ethicists, health disparity experts, clinicians and many others. We look forward to expanding our patient program as public health agencies grant us permission for more widespread vaccination. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWhere will patients go to get their COVID-19 vaccine?\n\n\n\n\n\n\nVaccines will be given to patients in our vaccine clinic on our Hyde Park medical campus. Patients selected through our lottery will get detailed information about where to go for their appointment. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWho can I call if I have questions about COVID-19 vaccination rollout?\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPlease contact the Illinois Department of Health COVID-19 Hotline at 800-889-3931 or email dph.sick@illinois.gov or the Chicago Department of Health at 312-746-4835 or email coronavirus@chicago.gov.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nMore COVID-19 Information From UChicago Medicine’s Experts:\n\nFrequently Asked Questions About the COVID-19 Vaccine\nHow Do Vaccines Work?\nWhat Are The Different Types Of Vaccines?\nHow Are Vaccines Made?\nHow Does The FDA Approve Vaccines?\nHow To Safely Interact With Family And Friends To Reduce Your COVID-19 Risk\nIs It COVID-19 Or The Flu? Only A Test Can Tell For Sure\nKeeping Up With Immunizations During The COVID-19 Pandemic\nCOVID-19 Testing Resources','No content','60637','5841 S Maryland Ave, Chicago, IL 60637, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:46:36','2021-02-27 04:41:08','UChicago Medicine','IL','div|col-sm-8 col-md-7'),(120,31,'https://www.sphp.com/health-and-wellness/coronavirus-vaccine/','No content','No content','12204','600 Northern Blvd, Albany, NY 12204, United States',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 13:47:49','2021-02-27 04:42:07','Albany Memorial Hospital','NY','-div|site-body'),(121,42,'https://www.tomthumb.com/pharmacy/covid-19.html','No content','No content','75252','18212 Preston Rd Dallas, TX 75252',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 14:04:42','2021-02-27 04:28:33','Tom Thumb Pharmacy','TX','div|column-control aem-GridColumn aem-GridColumn--default--12'),(123,4,'https://www.sutterhealth.org/for-patients/health-alerts/covid-19-vaccine','Limited COVID-19 Vaccine Availability\nThough COVID-19 continues to affect all of us, there’s hope on the horizon.\n                  Weve administered over 300,000 doses through our clinics and large-scale sites.\n\nDue to extremely limited supply, were not scheduling\n                  first dose appointments.\nPlease don’t call your provider – they cant give the vaccine or exceptions.\n\nWe appreciate your patience. Please check back often for updates.\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccine FAQs','No content','95405','Sonoma Ave, Santa Rosa, CA 95405, United States',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 14:06:34','2021-02-26 14:06:34','Sutter Health Organization','CA','div|split-container bg-gray'),(127,4,'https://www.chinesehospital-sf.org/covid-19-vaccine','You are hereHome » COVID-19 Resources » COVID-19 Vaccine \nCOVID-19 Vaccine\n\n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccine\n	LAST UPDATED: 2/4/2021, 9:00 a.m. \n\n	 \n\n	Were committed to offer vaccines to our patients, community, and staff. We have now begun vaccinating Chinese Hospital patients age 65 and older.\n\n	 \n\n\n		We have limited vaccine supply. Right now, were following state recommendations to prioritize vaccine appointments for:\n\n\n			Healthcare workers\n\n			Long-term care patients and staff\n\n			Emergency medical services\n\n			Chinese Hospital patients age 65 and older\n\n\n\nAre you a Chinese Hospital Health Systems patient and aged 65 and over?\n\n			Please call 1-628-228-2828 to schedule an appointment. Note that supplies are limited and may be prioritized based on state guidelines.\n\n			 \n\n\nUntil many more people are vaccinated, continue to protect yourself and your community by wearing a mask, social distancing, and washing your hands. Keep checking this page for updates.\nCalifornia’s vaccination plan\n\nBenefits of getting vaccinated\nCOVID-19 vaccines are meant to prevent you from getting COVID-19 and from spreading it to others. The ability of COVID-19 vaccines to protect us from spreading the virus to others is not yet known, but is being studied carefully.\nRead more at CDC’s Benefits of Getting a COVID-19 Vaccine.\nHow they work\nVaccines help our immune system fight infections in the future. COVID-19 vaccines will protect us from the virus that causes COVID-19 without having to get the illness.\nIt typically takes a few weeks after the last dose in a series to become fully protected. On the days after taking the vaccine, you may have a sore arm, aches, fatigue or fever, but these are not harmful. These symptoms signal that your immune system is developing protection from the virus.\nFrequently Asked Questions\n \n\n繁體中文\n \n\n \n\n\n\n \n \n\n\n \n\n\n\n\nMenu - Secondary\n\n\nOur Response to COVID-19\nCOVID-19 Testing Services\nCOVID-19 Vaccine\nWhat You Need To Know\nHow You Can Help','No content','94133','845 Jackson St, San Francisco 1-415-982-2400',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 14:21:54','2021-02-26 14:37:41','Chinese Hospital','CA','div|content-sidebar-wrap'),(128,31,'https://www.northwell.edu/coronavirus-covid-19/vaccine','','No content','10075','100 E 77th St New York, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 14:42:31','2021-02-26 14:42:31','Lenox Hill Hospital','NY','div|'),(132,4,'https://www.ucsfhealth.org/covid/vaccine','COVID-19 Information for Patients & Visitors \n\n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccines at UCSF Health','No content','94143','505 Parnassus Ave, San Francisco, CA 94143, United States',1,NULL,'2021-02-26 15:46:07','2021-02-26 15:46:07','UCSF Health','CA','div|component article-hero basic-hero'),(133,31,'https://www.rumcsi.org/about/covid-19-support/covid-19-vaccinations/','Home » About » COVID-19 Support » COVID-19 Vaccinations\n\n\n\n\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccinations\n\nRichmond University Medical Center is providing COVID-19 vaccines on a scheduled basis and in accordance with all New York State Department of Health (NYS DOH) guidelines. To determine if you meet the most current eligibility requirements, please refer to the New York State website.\nOur appointment dates and times will vary depending on the availably of the vaccine supply. We can only make appointments when our vaccine supply has been confirmed. Appointment dates and times will vary depending on the availably of the vaccine supply.\nTo make an appointment, please call and leave a message at (718) 818-3193. Please speak slowly and clearly. Your call will be returned in the order it was received.\nOnce you have an appointment, you wi