416 cases6 daily new cases73 deaths\nPutnam423 cases0 daily new cases3 deaths\nMarshall847 cases2 daily new cases14 deaths\nLast updated at 02/27/2021 6:27:38 pm\n\nView Interactive Map at IDPH\n\n* Testing through commercial labs is not required to be reported to BPMHD, however, we will still be notified of any positive cases from IDPH State Lab or commercial labs.\n\nCOVID-19 Vaccine Information\nIDPH: COVID-19 Vaccine FAQ\nCDC: Frequently Asked Questions about COVID-19 Vaccination\nCDC: Facts about COVID-19 Vaccines\nIDPH: SARS-CoV-2/COVID-19 Mass Vaccination Planning Guide\n\n\nThe Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) is a respiratory illness that can spread from person to person. The virus that causes COVID-19 is a novel coronavirus that was first identified in Wuhan, China.\nCOVID-19 has spread throughout the world, including the United States, since it was distinguished and was stated a public health emergency for the U.S. on January 31, 2020 to aid the nationâs healthcare community in responding to the threat.\nThe World Health Organization announced March 11, 2020 that the spread of coronavirus qualifies as a global pandemic.\nIn addition, Governor JB Pritzker delivered a disaster proclamation on March 9, 2020 concerning COVID-19 gives the state access to federal and state resources to combat the spread.\nOn Friday, March 13, Governor Pritzker announced all schools will close from Tuesday, March 17 thought Monday, March 30 to help prevent the spread of COVID-19 across Illinois.\nView the Governorâs news release.\nOn Sunday, March 15, Govenor Pritzker ordered all Illinois bars and restaurants to close to the public as of close of business Monday, March 16 through March 30.View the Governorâs news release.\nThe Bureau, Putnam, Marshall County Health Departments, along with local health departments in the region, local healthcare partners, the Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH) and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) are observing this closely and working to protect the publicâs health.\nCOVID-19 Symptoms:\nIndividuals who become sick with COVID-19 develop mild to severe respiratory illness with symptoms of:\n\nfever\ncough\ndifficulty breathing\n\n* These symptoms may appear 2-14 days after exposure (based on the incubation period of MERS-CoV viruses).\nHow Does It Spread?\nEven though the virus that causes COVID-19 probably emerged from an animal source, it is now spreading from person to person. It is thought to spread mainly between individuals who are within six feet of one another through respiratory droplets produced when an infected person coughs or sneezes. It is also possible that individuals can get COVID-19 by touching a surface or an object that has the virus on it and then continue to touch their own mouth, nose, and eyes. Although this is not thought to be the main way the virus spreads. Learn more here!\nWhat to do if you were potentially exposed to someone with confirmed COVID-19? Learn more here!\nHow Is It Treated?\nThere is not a specific antiviral treatment to treat COVID-19 at this time, though it is being studied. Individuals who are sick with COVID-19 should seek medical care from a health care professional to help relieve symptoms.\nHow Is COVID-19 Diagnosed?\nDiagnosis occurs through laboratory testing of respiratory specimens and serum (blood). At this time, the COVID-19 strain can only be detected at a public health laboratory.\nIs there any way for me to self-test?\nCurrently the CDC offers an online Coronavirus Self-Checker.\nThe purpose of the Coronavirus Self-Checker is to help you make decisions about seeking appropriate medical care. This system is not intended for the diagnosis or treatment of disease or other conditions, including COVID-19. This system is intended only for people who are currently located in the United States.\nThis project was made possible through a partnership with the CDC Foundation and is enabled by Microsoftâs Azure platform. CDCâs collaboration with a non-federal organization does not imply an endorsement of any one particular service, product, or enterprise.\nLearn more here!.\nHow Can I Protect Myself and My Family?\nAs with any respiratory virus, you can protect yourself and others by taking every day preventative actions:\n\nWash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water are not available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol.\nAvoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.\nAvoid close contact with people who are sick.\nStay home when you are sick.\nCover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash.\nClean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.\n\n** Please remember that it is also flu season and BPMHD recommends taking everyday preventive actions to stop the spread of germs, and taking flu antivirals if prescribed.\nDo I Need To Wear A Mask?\nThe BPMHD recommends face masks be used by people who show symptoms of COVID-19 to help prevent the spread to others. The use of facemasks is also crucial for health workers and people who are caring for an individual in a close setting; at home or in a health care facility.\nWhat Can Travelers Do To Protect Themselves and Others?\nIf you travel, take the following routine precautions:\n\nAvoid contact with sick people.\nAvoid touching your eyes, nose, or mouth with unwashed hands.\nClean your hands often by washing them with soap and water for at least 20 seconds or using an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains 60%â95% alcohol. Soap and water should be used if hands are visibly dirty.\nIt is especially important to clean hands after going to the bathroom; before eating; and after coughing, sneezing or blowing your nose.\n\nThe latest travel updates are available on CDCâs COVID-19 web page for travelers.\nWhat If I Recently Traveled To A Country Or Area Affected By COVID-19 And Got Sick?\nIf you were in a country or area with a COVID-19 outbreak and feel sick with fever, cough, or difficulty breathing, within 14 days after you left, you should:\n\nSeek medical advice â Call ahead before you go to a doctorâs office or emergency room. Tell them about your recent travel and your symptoms.\nAvoid contact with others.\nNot travel on public transportation while sick.\nCover your mouth and nose with a tissue or your sleeve (not your hands) when coughing or sneezing.\nWash hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds to avoid spreading the virus to others.\nWash your hands with soap and water immediately after coughing, sneezing or blowing your nose.\nIf soap and water are not readily available, you can use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains 60%â95% alcohol. Always wash hands with soap and water if hands are visibly dirty.\n\nOther Available Resources\nPrint Resources:\n\nWhat you need to know about COVID-19 (English, Spanish, Simplified Chinese)\nWhat to do if you are sick with COVID-19 (English, Spanish, Simplified Chinese)\nStop the Spread of Germs Poster (English, Spanish, Simplified Chinese)\nSymptoms of Coronavirus Disease 2019 Poster (English, Spanish, Simplified Chinese)\n\nWho Should I Call About COVID-19? Learn more here...\nInformation for Specific Groups:\n\nHigh Risk Individuals\nIndividual and Households\nPregnant Women and Children\nTravelers\n\nGuidance for Businesses\n\nRecommended Guidance for Preventing the Sptread of COVID-19 in Large Business\nBusiness and Employers\nIDPH Business and Organization Guidance\nGet Your Workplace Ready\nEssential Businesses & Operations Frequently Asked Questions\n\nResponse Partners\n\nState of Illinois and City of Chicago Issue New Guidance to Minimize COVID-19 Spread\n\nThe Bureau, Putnam and Marshall County Health Departments are working closely with our partner agencies to monitor for and prepare for COVID-19 to ensure the health and safety of our community. This page contains resources for our partners agencies in preparing, coordinating, and responding to the spread of COVID-19.\nGuidance for Healthcare Providers, Learn more here!.\nGuidance for First Responders\n\nCDC Guidance for Emergency Medical Services (EMS) Systems and 911 Public Safety Answering Points (PSAPs) for COVID-19\nWhat Fire Service and Emergency Medical Services Personnel Need to Know about Coronavirus Disease 2019\n\nGuidance for Law Enforcement\n\nWhat Law Enforcement Personnel Need to Know about Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)\n\nGuidance for Schools\n\nCDC Interim Guidance for Administrators of US Childcare Programs and K-12 Schools\nGet Your School Ready\nChecklist for Teachers, Parents, and Administrators\nFAQs for K-12 Schools and Childcare Program Administrators Coronavirus Disease-2019 (COVID-19)\nEnvironmental Cleaning and Disinfection Recommendations\nIDPH School Guidance\nIDPH COVID-19 Checklist (K-12 Administrators)\nSchools and Institutions of Higher Education\n\nGuidance for Communities\n\nMitigation Strategies for Communities with Local COVID-19 Transmission\nGet Your Community Ready\nGet Your Mass Gathering or Large Community Events Ready\n\nGuidance for Children/Daycare Centers\n\nApply for emergency day care license under emergency rules that DCFS posted on Friday March 20, 2020\nAdditional resources related to providing emergency day care services\nInterim Recommended Guidance for Preventing Spread of COVID-19 in Childcare/Daycare Centers\nChildcare for Essential Workers during COVID-19 Pandemic\n\nGuidance for Medically Fragile Child\n\nRecommended Guidance for Preventing Spread of COVID-19 in the Medically Fragile Child\n\nGuidance for the Oral Health Community\n\nRoutine Oral & Dental Health Guidelines\nGuidance for Oral Health\n\nGuidance for Faith-Based\n\nGet Your Community and Faith-Based Ready\nGuidance for Faith-Based\n\nGuidance for Funeral Homes\n\nGuidance for Funeral Homes\n\nGuidance for Homeless Shelters\n\nGuidance for Homeless Shelters\n\nGuidance fo