115 Conroe, TX 77304',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:04:07','2021-02-28 05:15:19','FAMILY FIRST URGENT CARE','TX','div|post-1831 page type-page status-publish hentry'),(452,31,'https://jamaicahospital.org/covid-19-resource-center/','Home\n       COVID-19 Resource Center\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWelcome to Jamaica Hospital’s COVID-19 Resource Center\nWe thank you for supporting our hospital as we continue to make necessary adjustments to properly protect and care for the health of our community. Here you can find the most recent updates and information pertaining to our hospital and clinics during this time.\nHealthcare Services Updates\nIt is important that you do not delay caring for your health. Many of our services have reopened, and we have put several protections in place to make our hospital safe for patients to seek in-person healthcare. Services that are now open to the public include our:\n\nAmbulatory Care Centers \nWomen’s Health Center \n Mental Health Clinic \n Ophthalmology Center \n Outpatient Rehabilitation Services \n\nWe are also now scheduling elective procedures in our  Ambulatory Surgery Centers , Radiology Department , and our Cardiology and Vascular Labs.\n \nTo schedule an appointment with one of our highly trained physicians please visit our home page and choose a specialty under “Clinical Services.” We also invite you to utilize our  Find A Doctor tool to search our directory of physicians by name, specialty, languages spoken and other criteria.\nOur Commitment To Safety\nJamaica Hospital has implemented strict safety precautions in accordance with CDC guidelines to protect the health of our patients, visitors and employees. To learn more about our measures to keep you safe, please click below:\n\n\n\n\nSAFETY PRECAUTIONS\n\n\n\n Modified Appointment Schedule – To eliminate overcrowding in our patient care areas, we are limiting appointments. This will reduce waiting times and help us manage proper social distancing policies.\n Pre-Registration – To avoid spending unnecessary time in waiting areas, patients will have the opportunity to complete all paperwork remotely before they arrive. \n Screenings – Designated hospital employees will greet all patients and screen them for COVID-like symptoms upon arrival. \n Disinfection and Cleaning – Our team remains dedicated to thoroughly and repeatedly disinfecting and cleaning all patient care areas in accordance with CDC guidelines. \n Limited Companions – For everyone’s safety and to avoid over crowding, only parents or other required companions are permitted to accompany patients during their appointments. \n Protective Equipment – All employees will be wearing appropriate level personal protective equipment (PPE) at all times. All patients will be required to wear a face mask as well. \n Working Together – All patients should monitor their health and report if they have tested positive for COVID-19, come in contact with someone who tested positive, or experienced any related symptoms in the last 14 days. \n\n\n\n\n\nTemporary Visitation Policies\nAs of Monday, June 22, we are allowing visiting hours on a limited basis on some patient units. All visitors are required to comply with our strict safety guidelines before being permitted on any patient units. Please Click Here to view our updated visitation hours and guidelines.\nCOVID Testing\nJamaica Hospital offers COVID testing for our patients. A COVID test can show if you have an active coronavirus infection and if you need to take the necessary steps to quarantine or isolate yourself from others.\nCOVID testing is available at all of our ambulatory care centers. Please visit the center closest to you to make an appointment. COVID testing is fully covered by insurance; if you do not have insurance however and would like to pay out-of-pock, the fee is $115.00\nAntibody Testing\nAn antibody test looks for antibodies that are made by your immune system in response to a threat, such as a specific virus. These antibodies can help prevent future infections.\nAntibody testing is available at all of our ambulatory care centers. Please visit the center closest to you to make an appointment. Antibody testing is fully covered by insurance; if you do not have insurance however and would like to pay out-of-pock, the fee is $50.00\nDonations\nServing one of the areas hit hardest by the COVID-19 pandemic, Jamaica Hospital’s front-line employees have been working tirelessly to treat the large number of patients and families affected by the Coronavirus outbreak. We are accepting donations to help us as we provide care to our community. Donate Now.\nUnderstanding Coronavirus\nTo help inform our community about the coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak, we have provided answers to the most frequently asked questions about the virus in this FAQ','No content','11418','8900 Van Wyck Expy Jamaica, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:05:37','2021-02-28 05:09:31','Jamaica Hospital','NY','div|col-md-9'),(453,42,'https://www.utphysicians.com/covid19vaccine/','No content','No content','77030','6410 Fannin Street | Houston, Texas 77030',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:05:48','2021-02-28 05:16:22','The University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston','TX','div|utpwrap'),(454,42,'https://vacstrac.hctx.net/landing','No content','No content','77027','2223 W Loop S, Houston, TX 77027, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:06:41','2021-02-28 05:20:55','Harris County Public Health','TX','div|content'),(455,42,'https://www.crofootmd.com/covid','No content','No content','77098','3701 Kirby Dr. Ste. 1230 Houston, TX 77098',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:07:27','2021-02-28 05:24:49','Gordon Crofoot Md Pa','TX','div|body-element'),(456,31,'https://nych.com/coronavirus-covid-19/','CORONAVIRUS COVID-19\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nSchedule Appointment for COVID19 Testing\nAt New York Community Hospital we are working together to protect our patients and staff.\n\nIF YOU WOULD LIKE TO DONATE SUPPLIES AND EQUIPMENT: \nPlease email kkofman@nych.com.\nPlease include the following information:\nContact name:\nContact phone number:\nType of item you would like to donate: \n\n\nBE INFORMED WITH UP TO DATE INFORMATION:\nIn order to be informed with up to date information regarding COVID-19, everyone is encouraged to visit the following sites:\nNew York State Department of Health\nNew York City Department of Health\nCDC – Center for Disease Control & Prevention\n\n\nPREVENTION\n\nNew Yorkers working together and staying home can slow the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19) in New York City. When you go out for essential needs, work or to get fresh air, keep distance between yourself and others and take the following precautions.\n• Keep at least 6 feet between yourself and others.\n• Wash your hands with soap and water often.\n• Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue or sleeve when sneezing or coughing.\n• Do not touch your face with unwashed hands.\n• Monitor your health more closely than usual for cold or ﬂu symptoms.\n\nIF YOU ARE SICK\n\n• Stay home.\n• If you have a cough, shortness of breath, fever, sore throat and do not feel better after 3-4 days, consult with your doctor.\n• If you need help getting medical care, call 311.\n• NYC will provide care regardless of immigration status or ability to pay\n\nPROTECT THE MOST VULNERABLE\n\n• Stay home if you have lung disease, heart disease, diabetes, cancer or a weakened immune system.\n• Stay home and call, video chat or text with family or friends who have one of these conditions.\nREDUCE OVERCROWDING\n• Stay home.\n• Telecommute if possible.\n   If you do go out:\n• Stagger work hours away from peak travel times.\n• Walk or bike.\n• Do not gather in crowds.\n\nCOVID ED NYCH','No content','11229','2525 Kings Hwy Brooklyn, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:12:01','2021-02-28 05:12:01','New York Community Hospital','NY','div|theme_page relative'),(457,31,'https://www.bronxcare.org/about-us/covid-19-testing/','No content','No content','10457','1650 Grand Concourse,Bronx, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:18:07','2021-02-28 05:18:07','Bronx Care','NY','div|page-wrap'),(458,46,'https://www.olympicmedical.org/covid-19-vaccine-information/','LATEST INFORMATION AND UPDATES | Centers for Disease Control | Department of Health | Coronavirus Response\n\n \n\n\nCLALLAM COUNTY VACCINE REGISTRATION (65+ YEARS)\nUpdated Feb. 26, 2021\nHow can I obtain the vaccine?\nThe Clallam County Department of Health and Human Services has elected to hold community vaccination clinics for individuals who are currently eligible for the COVID-19 vaccination in partnership with Olympic Medical Center and North Olympic Healthcare Network for the greater Port Angeles area, including Joyce, Jamestown Family Health Clinic in Sequim and Forks Community Hospital for residents of the West End.\nIndividuals must register in advance via Clallam County Health. REGISTER\nVaccinations are not available at Olympic Medical Physician clinics at this time. Individuals who are interested in receiving the vaccine and who are currently eligible can participate in the mass vaccination clinics in Port Angeles and Sequim.\nWho is currently eligible to receive the vaccine?\nIn the current phase of vaccinations, as prescribed by the Washington State Department of Health, all individuals 65 years or older are currently eligible.\n\n \n\n\nWhere can I be vaccinated?\n\n \n\n\nPort Angeles\nUpdated Feb. 26, 2021\nThose who were scheduled to receive a first dose of the Moderna vaccine on Feb. 13-14 will be able to reschedule to receive a first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Feb. 27-28. Registration for the Feb. 27-28 clinics will open on Feb. 24.\nIndividuals who wish to participate in these vaccinations must register online in advance.\n\nREGISTER\nELIGIBILITY \n\nClallam County residents\n65 years or older\n65 years or older\n50 years or older and living in a multigenerational household\n\nOMC SCHEDULE\nPfizer vaccine\n\nFebruary 27-28\nMarch 6-7\nMarch 27-28\n\nLOCATION\nPort Angeles High School Gymnasium\n304 E. Park Avenue\nPort Angeles, WA\nVACCINE\nOMC Vaccination Clinics: Pfizer\nNOHN Vaccination Clinics: Moderna\nOlympic Medical Center will provide staffing and supply of the Pfizer vaccine to eligible residents of the greater Port Angeles area, including Joyce – those 65 years or older – at the Port Angeles vaccination clinic on two weekends each month in February and March.\nOMC is planning to administer approximately 1,000 doses per day at the Port Angeles vaccination clinics.\nNorth Olympic Healthcare Network will provide staffing and supply of the Moderna vaccine at the Port Angeles vaccination clinic on the remaining two weekends in February and March.\nNOHN SCHEDULE\nModerna vaccine\n\nMarch 13-14\nMarch 20-21\n\n\n \n\n\nSequim\nUpdated Feb. 25, 2021\nREGISTER\nJamestown Family Health Clinic has announced details on upcoming vaccination clinics. For more information, see below and visit jamestownhealth.org. Individuals who wish to participate in these vaccinations must register online in advance.\nIndividuals seeking their second dose from the Jamestown Family Health Clinic should reference the date listed on the COVID-19 Vaccination Record Card they received after their first dose.\nELIGIBILITY\n\nSequim residents\n65 years or older, plus their domestic partner (regardless of age)\n\nUPCOMING FIRST DOSE CLINICS\nRegistration for the following dates opens on Wednesday, March 3 at 9:00 AM | REGISTER\n\nThursday, March 11, 8 AM – 1 PM\nSaturday, March 13, 8 AM – 1 PM\nTuesday, March 16, 8 AM – 1 PM\nThursday, March 18, 8 AM – 1 PM\nSaturday, March 20, 8 AM – 1 PM\n\nLOCATION\nCheck-In\nTrinity United Methodist Church,\n100 South Blake Avenue,\nSequim, WA\nVaccination\nJames Center For The Performing Arts,\n350 North Blake Ave,\nSequim, WA\nVACCINE\nModerna\nRegistration for the following dates opens on Wednesday, March 17 at 9:00 AM | REGISTER \n\nTuesday, March 30, 8 AM – 1 PM\nThursday, April 1, 8 AM – 1 PM\nSaturday, April 3, 8 AM – 1 PM\n\nRegistration for the following date (and additional April dates) opens on Wednesday, March 31 at 9:00 AM | REGISTER \n\nTuesday, April 6, 8 AM – 1 PM\n\nJamestown Family Health Clinic will offer Moderna vaccinations to residents of the Sequim area – individuals 65 years or older, plus their partner (regardless of age).\nOlympic Medical Center is providing additional staffing to support the Jamestown Family Health vaccination clinic in Sequim, beginning on February 2.\nFor more information, visit jamestownhealth.org.\n\n \n\n\nClallam Bay\nUpdated Feb. 26, 2021\nFork Community Hospital has recently offered vaccinations for West End residents in Forks and Clallam Bay. Details on future vaccination clinics on the West End will be posted when they are available.\nFor more information, visit forkshospital.org.\n\n \n\n\nWhat about residents of nursing homes?\nResidents and staff of nursing homes, assisted living facilities, and other senior congregate living settings, are currently eligible to receive the vaccine. Patients of OMP / OMC who live in one of these settings should direct their inquiries to customer contacts at these residences.\nWhere can I find more information?\n\nYou can visit our COVID site: olympicmedical.org/coronavirus.\nYou can also find information at our local health department: clallam.net/Coronavirus/vaccine.html\nThe Washington State DOH also has additional information: doh.wa.gov/Emergencies/COVID19/Vaccine\n\nPlease be patient as this is all very new and information is subject to change. Please contact us if you have further concerns or questions, and in the meantime, please continue to wear your mask, social distance and wash your hands.\n\n \n\n\nOMC Begins Vaccinating Front-Line Health Care Workers\nOlympic Medical Center began administering vaccines to front-line health care workers on Dec. 18. Samantha Counts, an RN in the Emergency Services department, became OMC’s first front-line health care worker to receive the COVID-19 vaccine.\n“It’s been a very stressful year, and we’re all very tired,” Counts said. “We’re all ready to put this behind us.”\n\n \n\n\nPhased Approach to COVID-19 Vaccination\nUpdated Jan. 19, 2021 // Dates listed with each tier are estimates\nGovernor Inslee announced on Jan. 18 a state-wide plan for widespread vaccine distribution and administration, which included changing the age threshold for those eligible to receive the vaccine in Phase 1B, Tier 1. All individuals 65 years or older all now eligible for vaccination. However, vaccinations clinics in Clallam County are currently offering the vaccine to individuals 70 years or older, according to local supply of the vaccine.\nOn Jan. 6, the Washington State Department of Health announced an estimated timeline for vaccinations in Phase 1B, Tiers 1, 2, 3 and 4. Information on who is eligible for vaccination in Phases 2, 3 and 4 will be announced soon by the DOH. For more information, visit CovidVaccineWA.org.\nThe Washington State Department of Health released on Dec. 10 (and updated on Dec. 30) COVID-19 vaccine allocation guidance for Phase 1A, Tiers 1 and 2.\n\n \n\n\nPhase 1A\nTiers 1 & 2 // December 2020\n\nHigh-risk workers in health care settings\nHigh-risk first responders\nResidents and staff of nursing homes, assisted living facilities, and other community-based, congregate living settings where most individuals over 65 years of age are receiving care, supervision, or assistance\nAll other workers at risk in health care setting\n\n\n \n\n\nPhase 1B\nTier 1 // January 2021\n\nAll people 65 years or older (updated Jan. 18)\nAll people 50 years or older in multigenerational households\n\nThe Washington State Department of Health has defined individuals at risk due to living in multigenerational households as follows:\n\nVulnerability – specifically, an older adult or elder who cannot live independently and is being cared for by a relative or inhome caregiver or being cared for by someone who works outside the home.\nRisk of exposure – specifically, an older adult or elder who is living with and taking care of kinship (along the lines of a\ngrandparent with a grandchild)\nThis group does not include an older adult who is able to live independently and is taking care of the individual’s\nkinship/children.\n\n\n\n\n\nTier 2 // February 2021\n\nHigh-risk critical workers 50 years or older who work in certain congregate settings: agriculture; food processing; grocery stores; K-12 (teachers and school staff); childcare; corrections; prisons, jails or detention centers; public transit; fire; law enforcement\n\nTier 3 // March 2021\n\nPeople 16 years or older with 2 or more co-morbidities or underlying conditions\n\nTier 4 // April 2021\n\nHigh-risk critical workers under 50 years who work in congregate settings (as noted in Phase 1B, Tier 2)\nPeople, staff and volunteers in congregate living settings: Correctional facilities, group homes for people with disabilities; people experiencing homelessness that live in or access services in congregate settings\n\n\n \n\n\nAs noted by the Department of Health, this approach prioritizes population groups that have been disproportionately impacted by COVID-19 due to external social factors and systemic inequities.\nEach group will become eligible for the vaccine one at a time and will continue to be eligible throughout the vaccine distribution.\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\n\n\nFDA Approves Emergency Use Authorizations for Two Vaccines\nUpdated Dec. 21 \nThe U.S. Food and Drug Administration has approved two emergency use authorizations for COVID-19 vaccines, first the Pfizer vaccine on Dec. 11 and, most recently, the Moderna vaccine on Dec. 18.\nThe first doses of the COVID-19 vaccine arrived in the state of Washington on Monday, Dec. 14. Olympic Medical Center expects to receive a distribution of 975 doses of the vaccine.\nOlympic Medical Center is prepared to administer approved vaccines according to the phased approach outlined in the CDC’s COVID-19 Vaccination Program.\nEach potential COVID-19 vaccine undergoes thorough clinical trials before the FDA reviews test results and any side effects in order to determine that it is safe and effective. If approved by the FDA, each vaccine also undergoes additional review by a multi-state vaccine workgroup, the COVID Vaccine Safety Review Workgroup. Washington is a part of the workgroup, along with California, Oregon and Nevada.\n\n \n\n\nOMC Readiness for COVID-19 Vaccine\nOMC has purchased and installed an ultra-low temperature freezer, which will be necessary to store the vaccine. The freezer is one of two known ultra-low temperature freezers in Clallam County.\nOMC has started administering vaccines, beginning with front-line health care workers who are at the most risk of being exposed to COVID-19, including, but not limited to, those who work in the emergency department, inpatient units, Walk-in Clinic and the COVID-19 testing site.\nAs supply of approved vaccines become more readily available and the vaccination program continues through each phase, OMC will be prepared to administer vaccines to each group and population in Clallam County.\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nHow Are COVID-19 Vaccines Made?\nVaccine testing and production are being done simultaneously to expedite the process of realizing an authorized vaccine for the public. Multiple COVID vaccines are being tested.\nEach vaccine goes through multiple clinical trials, starting first with small group of volunteers before expanding to a few hundred and eventually a few thousand volunteers.\nAfter successfully advancing through clinical trials, each vaccine must be approved by the FDA.\n\n \n\n\nCDC: Ensuring the Safety of COVID-19 Vaccines in the United States | Ensuring COVID-19 Vaccines Work\n\n \n\n\nHow will COVID-19 vaccines work?\nFrom the Washington State Department of Health, “The COVID-19 vaccine teaches your immune system to recognize the coronavirus. When you get the vaccine, your immune system makes antibodies (‘fighter cells’) that stay in your blood and protect you in case you are infected with the virus. You get protection against the disease without having to get sick.”\nMost COVID-19 vaccines are expected to be administered in two doses, separated by either 21 or 28 days. COVID-19 vaccines from different manufacturers will not be interchangeable; individuals must receive their second dose from the same manufacturer as the first dose. At the time of receiving the first dose, individuals will receive a second-dose reminder card, detailing the date of their first dose, vaccine manufacturer, lot number and the due date of their second dose.\n\n \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nLearn More About COVID-19 Vaccines\nLearn more about COVID-19 vaccines, how they are being made and tested, when they will be made available and how they will work.\n\n Washington State Department of HealthLEARN MORE \n\n\nCenters for Disease ControlLEARN MORE','No content','98362','928 Caroline St Port Angeles, WA',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:24:33','2021-02-28 05:24:33','Olympic Medical Center','WA','div|full_width_inner'),(459,31,'https://www.mountsinai.org/about/covid19/vaccine-information','Share\n\n\n\nFacebook\n\n\n\n\nTwitter\n\n\n\n\nLinkedin\n\n\n\n\nEmail\n\n\n\n\n\nHome\nAbout Us\nCOVID-19 Facts and Resources','No content','10025','1111 Amsterdam Avenue New York, NY 10025',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:25:13','2021-02-28 05:25:13','Mount Sinai Morningside','NY','div|full-width'),(460,31,'https://www.tbh.org/coronavirus','Practical Tips to Keep You and Your Family Safe\nHow to Help. We have been so heartened by the support of our community. Still want to help? We still need it. Check out ways to help.\n\nUPDATE — January 1, 2021\n\nVisiting Hours\nTo ensure a safe environment for everyone during this continuing pandemic, The Brooklyn Hospital Center has limited and restricted visitation except for the following situations:\n* A partner for the laboring parent.\n* Parents accompanying pediatric patients.\n* Family members of patients at imminent end-of-life.\n* Patients for whom a support person has been deemed to be essential to care (medically necessary) including patients with intellectual and/or developmental disabilities, and cognitive impairments including dementia.\nThank you for your cooperation and understanding.\n\nUPDATE — September 2020\nKeeping family and friends healthy is our mission. And we do that by keeping our spaces clean. That is our commitment to you.\n\n\n\n\nUPDATE — June 2020\nA Letter from Our President & CEO\nMoving Forward: A Hospital Within a Hospital\nWe hope you and your family are in good health. We have all been through a lot these last few months and are all looking forward to resuming more normal routines. While many things have changed, one thing remains constant: TBHC’s commitment to Keeping Brooklyn Healthy\nOur healthcare workers have heroically fought on the frontlines of the COVID-19 battle, and we remain here for those who continue to come in with COVID. But we also need to return to providing care for those patients getting a knee replaced, seeking relief for a painful spine debilitation, or considering life-preserving weight-loss surgery. We serve our community’s healthcare needs in a myriad of ways. As COVID-19 remains in the community until a vaccine is created, we know you have a multitude of questions about how TBHC will continue to deliver safe, effective and compassionate care. Let’s tackle those questions here:\nWhat do you mean by a hospital within a hospital?As soon as it is allowed by the State of New York, TBHC will phase in elective surgeries and procedures. Because TBHC continues to manage COVID-19 patients, the hospital has created a “COVID-safe” environment by organizing the hospital into separate areas with distinct access points, designated waiting areas, staff, nursing units and equipment. We will be effectively treating the needs of both sets of patients in separate and safe models of care.\nWhen is the hospital transitioning to this new model?TBHC is already performing a number of urgent and emergency surgeries and procedures following best practices around COVID screening and safety protocols. Full capacity for elective surgeries and procedures is anticipated for the near future.\nHow will the Emergency Room handle COVID safely?The Emergency Room will safely handle both COVID-19 and non-COVID cases in the following ways:\n\nEveryone, staff and patients alike, must wear masks. If you do not have one, you will be provided with one.\nWhen you arrive, you will be screened for possible COVID-19 or other contagious illness.\nIf it is determined your condition is not related to a contagious illness:\n\nYou will be directed to our waiting area, which will only allow patients with non-contagious illness. There, you will be asked to observe social distancing according to marks on the floor or staff direction.\nYou will be treated in a safe and separate treatment area for all your emergencies not related to a contagious illness. We have and will maintain this safe zone at all times, even during a crisis.\n\n\nIf it is suspected you have a contagious illness, you will immediately be taken to a safe and separate evaluation-treatment area.\nWe also have a safe, separate evaluation and treatment areas for pediatric emergencies with its own separate entrance.\nFurther note that all staff will at all times wear masks and gloves and frequently wash their hands. Staff who register you will be behind a plexiglass shield to keep all safe and protected.\nOnly one caregiver is allowed with a patient. Caregivers will also be screened. To protect everyone’s safety, visitors will be limited and authorized on a case-by-case basis, depending on the emergency.\n\nWho will be screened and tested for COVID-19?\n\nAs a precaution, all patients and visitors will be screened for COVID-19 symptoms at all access points to the hospital and ambulatory sites.\nAs of April 24, all admitted patients are tested for COVID-19.\nTBHC has initiated antibody testing for all front-line employees.\nTelemedicine visits are available for patients, as well as COVID-19 screening.\n\nHave you cleaned the hospital well?Every room and public area in the hospital is cleaned and disinfected daily following a rigorous infection protocol. Patient, procedure and operating rooms are intensively cleaned and disinfected to the highest levels. The walls and floors are disinfected, and everything is stripped from the room. The crew sweeps through on a clockwise rotation to make sure nothing is missed. As a final layer of protection, each room is misted with a deep-cleaning chemical to kill any remaining virus.\nWhen are the TBHC ambulatory sites opening?\n\nAmbulatory sites are now open with modifications to ensure your safety.\nAppointments are being scheduled to assure that a safe number of patients are allowed in the waiting room at any one time and that social distancing can be maintained at all times by both patients and staff. Masks are required to be worn by all patients and those accompanying patients at the visit. All staff are wearing masks, as well.\nOnly one parent or caregiver is allowed with a patient, including one for an elderly or handicapped patient, and one to accompany a pregnant woman during prenatal visits.\nPatient exam rooms will be closely monitored throughout the day and disinfected as needed. The waiting areas and common areas will be cleaned and disinfected periodically during the day and each evening.\n\nWhat further assurances are there for non-COVID-19 patients who require elective surgeries or procedures at TBHC?\n\nAll staff working in pre-surgical testing and perioperative areas are being screened and tested for COVID antibodies.\nAll patients will be provided with an appropriate mask if they do not have one at their appointment.\nThere will be separate PACU (recovery) and nursing units for COVID-19 versus non-COVID patients\nTBHC has adequate and separate ICU capacity and staff for both COVID-19 and non-COVID patients.\nAll patients will be tested for COVID-19 48 hours before surgery/procedure.\n\nIf positive and symptomatic, the procedure will be rescheduled.\nIf positive and non-symptomatic, TBHC will proceed with the case.\n\n\n\nStay safe and be well,\nGary G. TerrinoniPresident and CEOThe Brooklyn Hospital Center\n\nUPDATE — May 4, 2020:Effective, May 4, the COVID-19 screening tent outside the emergency room will close.​ If you want to learn more about your risk for COVID-19 or have questions about testing, please call the Community Hotline at 718-250-8199.\n\nUPDATE — APRIL 15, 2020:TBHC Blood Bank is seeking plasma donors who have recovered from COVID-19. Anyone who has had COVID-19 may qualify to donate blood and participate in TBHCs \"convalescent plasma\" program for treatment of patients who are currently very ill. Those who have already had the infection usually have high quantities of antibodies in their blood, which are potentially a powerful weapon against the disease.​ To qualify, you must have had a positive test AND be asymptomatic for at least 14 days. You do not have to have a negative test to prove you have cleared the virus. Convalescent Plasma COVID-19 Donor Request Form. On the referral form, where they ask what organization referred you, please choose “OTHER” and type TBHC or The Brooklyn Hospital Center.\nAbout the Coronavirus Community Hotline: 718-250-8199\nA telemedicine community hotline has been put in place. If you believe you have COVID-19 symptoms or have been exposed to the virus, you can now be pre-screened on the phone. Call us at 718-250-8199 from 9 am to 6 pm daily.\n \nCDC (Center for Disease Control) Updates\nNew York State Department of Health Updates\nNYC General Updates\nCoronavirus Hotline: 1-888-364-3065\nwhere New Yorkers with questions about the virus can speak with public health experts in their preferred language.\nNew Yorkers can also text COVID to 692-692 to get regular updates on the latest developments.','No content','11217','86 St Felix St Brooklyn, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 05:29:34','2021-02-28 05:29:34','The Brooklyn Hospital Center','NY','div|pane-content'),(461,31,'https://www.kingsbrook.org/Latest-News/Press-Releases/2021/Kingsbrook-Provided-COVID-19-Vaccinations-to-Com.aspx','KINGSBROOK PROVIDES COVID-19 VACCINES FOR THE COMMUNITY! \n\nDedicated nurses and pharmacy staff at Kingsbrook Jewish Medical Center\r\n	 geared up this weekend to provide COVID-19 vaccinations for our community.\r\n	 The overwhelming response of residents made it so that staff worked around\r\n	 the clock 7am-8pm to facilitate the pivotal need.\nCommunity residents can be seen here holding their \"Ive been\r\n	 vaccinated\" cards to encourage others in the community to stay safe\r\n	 and help fight COVID-19. For more information about COVID vaccination\r\n	 activities at Kingsbrook please call 718-604-5300.\nUpdates regarding new vaccination dates and times for the community will\r\n	 be announced.','No content','11203','585 Schenectady Ave Brooklyn, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:03:09','2021-02-28 06:03:09','Kingsbrook Jewish Medical Center','NY','div|press-content cf'),(462,31,'https://www.mskcc.org/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine','COVID-19 Vaccine Information for Patients','No content','10065','1275 York Ave New York, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:08:32','2021-02-28 06:08:32','Memorial Sloan Kettering Cancer Center','NY','div|msk-hero__inner'),(463,42,'https://everydayrx.com/covid19-vaccine-wait-list/','This site does not sell Covid-19 Vaccinations for Personal or Home Administration\nCovid-19 Vaccinations are provided by a Licensed Vaccination Authorized Pharmacy Only during your onsite appointment at the local pharmacy.\nPlease be aware that Texas DSHS has allocated COVID-19 Vaccines only to Vaccine Hubs throughout the state for Phase 1A: Front-Line Healthcare Workers and Residents at Long-Term Care Facilities and 1B: People over 65 or with a Chronic Medical Condition that puts them at increased risk for severe illness from COVID-19.\nAt this time, we do not know when the COVID-19 Vaccine will be made available to Community Pharmacies.\nWe strongly recommend to anyone who is eligible for Phase 1A or 1B to register at your nearest Vaccine Hub by visiting the Texas Department of State Health Services website here: https://dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/immunize/vaccine-hubs.aspx\nYou may continue to sign up for our Vaccine Waiting List below and we will notify you when we begin receiving the COVID-19 Vaccine.','No content','75224','2701 S Hampton Rd Ste 100 Dallas, TX 75224',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:28:02','2021-02-28 07:07:19','Hampton Apothecary Lp','TX','div|fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-4 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-flex-column'),(464,42,'https://neighborcare.org/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine/','COVID-19 Vaccine Information \nTo translate this information, select language at the top of the page.\nPara traducir esta información, seleccione el idioma en la parte superior de la página.\nSi aad u tarjunto macluumaadkan, ku xulo luqadda kore ee bogga.\nĐể dịch thông tin này, chọn ngôn ngữ ở đầu trang.\nUpdated 2-23-21 \nCOVID-19 vaccines have been authorized by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for emergency use and limited supplies are available in Washington state. Vaccines are an important way we protect ourselves and our patients, especially communities of color who have been disproportionately impacted by COVID. By getting people vaccinated, we can save lives, reduce the spread, and begin to reverse the harms caused to mental health and economic stability as a result of necessary community restrictions.   \nWe plan to have vaccines available for our eligible patients this spring (depending on state vaccine supply). \nCome back to this page for updates on who is eligible for vaccines and where to get vaccinated. \nVisit FindYourPhaseWA.org to check your eligibility or see the Department of Health vaccine phases below (also Spanish). Find vaccine locations and other info at COVDVaccine.org. Search for appointments at CovidWA.com.\n\nThere is also a lot of false information about the vaccine online. Always check the source of that claim. Watch this video for tips on how to determine if a claim is true or not. \n\nFrequently Asked Questions\nFor frequently asked questions in other languages scroll to the bottom of the Public--Health Seattle & King Countys website.\nPrint these FAQs (PDF)','No content','75212','2261 Singleton Blvd, Dallas, TX 75212, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:30:04','2021-02-28 07:08:38','Neighborcare Clinic','TX','div|body-holder'),(465,42,'https://www.healthcoreweb.com/covid-19/','No content','No content','75231','8210 Walnut Hill Lane, Suite 230  |  Dallas, Texas 75231',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:30:58','2021-02-28 07:09:33','Healthcore Physicians Group','TX','div|entry-content'),(466,42,'https://purpleheartspc.com/covid-19','No content','No content','75051','688 West Pioneer Parkway Suite 120 , Grand Prairie, Texas 75051, United States',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:31:48','2021-02-28 07:10:44','Purple Hearts Primary Care Services Pllc','TX','div|x-el x-el-section c1-1 c1-2 c1-3 c1-h c1-i c1-b c1-c c1-k c1-l c1-d c1-e c1-f c1-g'),(467,42,'https://www.brookshires.com/covid-19-information','No content','No content','75154','105 E Ovilla Rd, Red Oak, TX 75154, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:32:37','2021-02-28 07:06:31','Brookshires Pharmacy 108','TX','div|main-content child'),(468,31,'http://www.sbhny.org/','COVID-19 Virus Testing and Vaccine [updated 3/1/2021] \n\n\nCOVID-19 Virus Testing:\nCommunity testing for the COVID-19 virus is available by appointment at the SBH Ambulatory Care Center, 1st Floor, 4487 Third Avenue on Monday to Friday from 1 – 5 p.m. Call (718) 960-3730.\nCOVID-19 Vaccine:\nSBH is administering the COVID-19 vaccine to people who live or work in New York based on guidance provided by the NYS Department of Health. We are committed to serving our patients and community members as vaccine supplies are made available.\nPlease complete our Vaccination Request Form to join our waiting list. A member of our scheduling team will call you to set up an appointment. Please note, we are not scheduling vaccine appointments through calls to SBH.\nCOVID-19 vaccines are administered at the SBH Health and Wellness Center, 4507 Third Avenue, Bronx, NY. The Center is located directly across the street from St. Barnabas Hospital.\nThe NYS Department of Health requires that you bring a government issued ID that confirms your age if you are age 65 or older. If you are under 65, you should bring proof of eligibility. This can include: an employee ID card, a letter from an employer or affiliated organization, or a pay stub. For people with underlying health conditions, a letter from your doctor is not required to demonstrate eligibility to receive the COVID-19 vaccine. At your vaccine appointment, you will be asked to complete a certification form confirming your eligibility.\nVisit this link for New York State’s eligibility criteria for the COVID-19 vaccine.\nPlease continue to check this website for updates and submit any questions to SBHCovidVaccine@sbhny.org.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  David Perlstein, MD, CEO\nTalks about the SBH Health and Wellness Center\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n Dr. Janine Adjo, Chair, Department of Pediatrics Answers your questions about the Covid-19 vaccine\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWe are Open, Safe and Ready to Help You\n\n\nFrom the ER, to ambulatory care, to our inpatient rooms, we at SBH Health System have taken every precaution to make sure we are open, safe, and ready to help you with your healthcare needs.\nWe’ve learned a great deal from the pandemic and have put in place thoughtful and structured policies and procedures to protect both our patients and staff. Safety continues to come first at SBH to ensure the highest quality care, protection, support and comfort for you and your family.\nThis has ranged from the spacing of our ambulatory care waiting room seating to allow for social distancing, to new staff and patient screening procedures, to a rigorous deep cleaning of our facility that includes the use of UV-C light to kill off Covid-19 and other pathogens. If you need to see a doctor, come and see us – whether it’s in person or virtually through telehealth. We’re ready to help.\nClick here for the Visitor Policy as of June 19, 2020.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n Apply\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n Nursing Opportunities\n\n\n\n\n\nOur DRIVEto Patient Centered ExcellenceWE STRIVEto be the healthcare system of choice in the BronxLEADING THE WAYin Chronic Disease Management, Visit our Center for Comprehensive CareOUR NEW LOOKSchedule a Tour of Our New Maternity Suite\n\n\n\n\n\nPatient Care\nFind out about our new Lung Cancer Screening Program, get directions to our locations, access Follow My Health, find services for your medical, surgical, behavioral and emergency needs, and much more.\n\nRead More\n\n\n\n\n\nHealthcare Professionals\nExplore new opportunities. Become a valued team member and make a difference in our community.\n\nRead More\n\n\n\n\n\nCareers at SBH\nBecome a member of the SBH Health System family. We offer many exciting opportunities for clinical and non-clinical professionals to make a difference for our patients.\n\nRead More\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\nFind a Doctor \nSearch for a doctor by name or specialty.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\nPhysician Referrals \nRequest additional services for your patients\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n \n\n\nCommunity \nLearn about the health needs of your Bronx community.\n\n\n\n\n\n Donate to the SBH Health and Wellness 20/20/20 Campaign\n\n Pay Your Bill\nLatest News\n\n\n\n\n\n\n16 Dec 20\nNo Comments\n\n\n\n \n\n\nStaff at the hospital began to receive the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine.\n\n\n\n\nA momentous day at SBH, staff at the hospital began to receive the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine. Nursing supervisor Clover Mclennon was the first person at SBH to get the vaccine.\n\n\n\nBlog News Read More\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n26 Oct 20\nNo Comments\n\n\n\n \n\n\nWomen’s Center Imaging Center at the  new SBH Health and Wellness Center\n\n\n\n\nDr. Bert Petersen and Dr. Ruth Cassidy give News 12 a tour through the soon-to-open Women’s Imaging Center at the new SBH Health and Wellness Center, stressing the importance of the advanced technology that will be offered here.\n\n\n\nBlog News Read More\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n12 Oct 20\nNo Comments\n\n\n\n \n\n\nSBH Center For Wound Healing/Hyperbaric Medicine Names New Director\n\n\n\n\nDr. Ronald McLean has been named the new director of the Center for Wound Healing and Hyperbaric Medicine at SBH Health System, replacing the late Dr. Ronald Verrier. A general and trauma surgeon at SBH since 2002, Dr. McLean began…\n\n\n\nBlog News Read More\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n7 Oct 20\nNo Comments\n\n\n\n \n\n\nSBH named winner in this year’s Community Health Improvement Award and Pinnacle Award for Quality and Patient Safety\n\n\n\n\nThe Hospital Association of New York State (HANYS) has named SBH a winner in this year’s Community Health Improvement Award and Pinnacle Award for Quality and Patient Safety for its new definition of ‘clean’ — use of adenosine triphosphate bioluminescence…\n\n\n\nBlog News Read More\n\n\n\n\nShow all news\n\nSBH Bronx Health Talk\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nTranscripts\n\n\n\n\n\n\nSBH Health System\n\n\n\n\nSt Barnabas Hospital\nSBH Ambulatory Care\nSBH Hemodialysis Center\nSBH Behavioral Health\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nby phone: +1-718-960-3730\n\nfor emergencies: +911\n\n\n\n\n\nQuick Links\n\n\nListen to our new podcast\nSBH Bronx Health Talk\n\n\n\n\nFind out about the SBH Wellness Center\n\n\n\n\nDonate to our Covid-19 Efforts\n\n\n\n\nNew York Medical Journal\n\n\n\n\nCentering Pregnancy\nComing to SBH\n\n\n\n\nSBH Auxiliary\n\n\n\n\nFollowMyHealth\n\n\n\n\nGetting Here\n\n\n\n\nHospice of New York\n\n\n\n\nBeFitNYC\n\n\n\n\nMedia Requests\n\n\n\n\nSurprise Bills Law\n\n\n\n\nVolunteering\n\n\n\n\nMaternity Tours\n\n\n\n\nTours are suspended until further notice due to COVID-19 precautions.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nNICHE\n\n\nSBH is now a NICHE-designated hospital.  NICHE designation – which stands for Nurses Improving Care for Healthsystem Elders – demonstrates a hospital’s commitment and continued progress in improving quality, enhancing the patient and family experience, and supporting the hospital’s efforts to serve its communities.  NICHE’s vision is for all patients ages 65 and over to be given sensitive and exemplary care.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nDermatology \nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nEmergency Medicine\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nFamily Practice\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nGeneral Practice Dental\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nInternal Medicine\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nONMM\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPediatric Dental\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPediatrics\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPharmacy\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPodiatry\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nPsychiatry\nResidency Program\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nSurgery\nResidency Program','No content','10457','4422 3rd Ave Bronx, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 06:55:13','2021-02-28 06:55:13','St Barnabas Hospital','NY','div|page-wrap'),(469,4,'http://www.reliablerexall.com/','About Us\nReliable Rexall Sunset\nPharmacy is an independent pharmacy in the inner sunset neighborhood of\nSan Francisco. The location has been a pharmacy since 1959, with several\ndifferent pharmacies operating during that time. Most recently, in July 2016 Sean and Will opened Reliable Rexall Sunset Pharmacy. \n \nSean and Will, both New Zealand\npharmacists, are always happy to chat about your health and wellness. Our goal\nis to help improve your health, through both traditional and complimentary\ntherapies.\n \nWe\nalso offer a unique concierge compounding service\nfor medications not available commercially including medications for your pets; a med sync program\nthat refills your prescriptions faster and easier; blister packs to\nhelp organize your daily medications; and we deliver locally to\nSF residents.\nThe\nstore carries a wide range of OTC medications, nutraceuticals, vitamins,\nsklncare, haircare, womens and mens health, toiletries, travel packs, lotto,\ngift cards, stationary, food & beverage and much more.\nCall in and say hi, youre always\nwelcome.','No content','94122','801 Irving St San Francisco,CA 94122-2310',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 07:05:18','2021-02-28 07:05:18','Reliable Rexall Sunset Pharmacy','CA','div|Home-AboutUs'),(470,31,'https://wellnow.com/covid-19/','COVID-19 Testing FAQ\n\n\n\n\nHow do I check in for COVID-19 testing? \n\n\nAppointments are encouraged for COVID-19 testing, which can be scheduled on the location page of your nearest center or by phone. Upon arrival, please respond to your appointment text with “here” and wait in your car until you receive further instruction.\n\n\nWhat are the differences between the antibody and molecular tests? \n\nCOVID-19 PCR molecular testing directly screens for the virus using a culture obtained from a nasal swab.  It indicates if a patient currently has the virus.  This test is available at all WellNow centers with results returned to the patient in 3-5 days.\nCOVID-19 rapid molecular or swab testing also directly indicates if a patient currently has the virus using a nasal swab. Results are returned to the patient in 15 minutes or less. This test is available at our Oswego and Oneonta centers, and administered using Abbott ID NOW.\nCOVID-19 rapid antigen testing indicates if a patient currently has the virus using a nasopharyngeal swab.  Results are returned to the patient in 15 minutes or less.  A confirmatory PCR test may be required, with results returned to the patient in 3-5 days.  This rapid test is available at all WellNow centers and administered using the CareStart™ antigen test by AccessBio.\nAntibody testing uses a blood sample to indirectly screen for COVID-19 by looking for antibodies produced as the body’s response to a COVID-19 infection.  A positive or negative result from antibody testing alone is not enough to confirm presence or absence of infection, ongoing infection and/or long-term immunity.  Results are returned to the patient within 3-5 days.\nThere is still much to be learned from this virus, and accordingly, patients should still practice social distancing, wearing masks, frequent hand washing, avoiding touching their face, and following all other local health department guidelines to help reduce the spread of the virus.  For more information regarding COVID-19, please visit the CDC.\n\nWho can receive a COVID-19 test at WellNow? \n\n\nTesting is available to anyone who has or recently had symptoms of COVID-19, or anyone who may have been exposed to someone confirmed positive for COVID-19, with no prescription required. A WellNow provider will see you to help determine which test is best for you.\n\nThe number of times you can be tested will be determined by a WellNow provider. After an evaluation, this decision will be based on your symptoms and their duration. Certain essential-services personnel may need to be tested more than once.\n\nHow much does COVID-19 testing cost at WellNow? \n\nTesting may be covered based on insurance coverage as part of the CARES Act.  Contact your insurance carrier for full details on your coverage.\nFor patients without insurance, testing costs $100 for the PCR swab test, $43 for the antibody test, and $60 for the rapid swab and antigen tests, all in addition to the charge for the base visit and any other necessary services.\nPlease note, at this time rapid testing is available for those whose insurance carrier currently reimburses WellNow for the full cost of the rapid test.\n\nHow long will it take to receive my COVID-19 testing results? \n\nResults for both the COVID-19 PCR swab test and antibody test will return within 3-5 days. Patients in New York can get their results by registering for an account at www.mybostonheart.com 2-3 days after the sample was taken.\nRapid testing is currently available at 11 of our locations with results in 15 minutes. A confirmatory PCR test may be required, which results in 3-5 days.\nIf after 7 days you are still unable to obtain your results or are experiencing trouble with the portal, please contact the WellNow center where you were tested so we can help provide more information Please note that all positive COVID-19 PCR swab test results will receive a direct phone call from one of our team members. Patients in Chicago will receive all results directly from WellNow.\n\nAre your centers following safety and sanitary guidelines? \n\nBecause your health is our priority, we are following all sanitary guidelines from the CDC and local health departments in our facilities with:\n\nReinforced disinfecting processes across all rooms, tables, chairs, computers, door handles and surfaces with EPA-registered cleaning products.\nProviding personal protective equipment (PPE) for our staff and requiring all patients to wear masks upon entering a WellNow center or we are happy to provide you with one.\nExpanded telehealth services and accepted insurances from WellNow Virtual Medical to ensure our providers are available for those who need or prefer to receive care from home.\n\n\nWhere is Rapid Testing available? \n\nAt this time, rapid testing is available at all WellNow centers.\nPlease note, if your rapid antigen test results negative, we are required to send a confirmatory PCR molecular test to our lab partner. For your convenience, we will swab you for both tests during your visit. The rapid antigen test will return results in 15 minutes and the confirmatory test will return results in 3-5 days.\nRapid Molecular testing is available at our centers in Oswego and Oneonta, with results available in 15 minutes.','No content','12110','800 Loudon Rd Latham, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 07:06:37','2021-02-28 07:06:37','WellNow Urgent Care - Latham','NY','div|accordion-group'),(471,43,'https://www.seuhealth.com/covid-vaccine','','No content','84501','28 S 100 E, Price, UT 84501, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 07:15:37','2021-02-28 07:18:23','Southeastern Utah Health Department','UT','div|_2iB5S'),(472,31,'http://www.ellismedicine.org/covid19/staff.aspx','','No content','12110','800 Loudon Rd Latham, NY',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 07:17:59','2021-02-28 07:17:59','Ellis Hospital','NY','div|nav-color-bar'),(473,43,'https://slco.org/health/COVID-19/vaccine/','COVID Vaccine\n\nUpdated February 25, 2021\n\nPeople 65 and Older: Make a first-dose vaccine appointment. Call 385-468-7468 if you prefer to not schedule online; please be prepared for long wait times if you choose to call.\nPeople 16+ who have a qualifying medical condition: Learn when and how to make a first-dose vaccine appointment. Note that people under 18 will require parental consent at the time of vaccination, and they are only eligible to receive the Pfizer vaccine.\nHealthcare Workers: We no longer have first-dose appointments for healthcare workers. You may be vaccinated by a local pharmacy listed below under Other Sources for Vaccine.\nSecond Doses: You will have the opportunity to make your second-dose appointment at the time you receive your first dose. If you did not schedule your second dose at the time of your first dose, call 385-468-7468. The appointment line is staffed Monday through Friday from 8am to 5pm and Saturday from 10am to 6pm. You may only schedule your second dose AFTER youve received your first dose.\nOther Sources for Vaccine: Some Salt Lake County locations of the below retail pharmacies are offering vaccine to the eligible priority groups.\n\nDans Fresh Market\nFresh Market\nHarmons\nMaceys\nSmiths\nWalgreens\nWalmart\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWhen and where can I be vaccinated?\n Because Utah currently has a limited supply of COVID vaccine, the Utah Department of Health is prioritizing who will receive the vaccine when.\n\nUtahns 65 and Older can be vaccinated now. Make a vaccine appointment here.\nUtahns 16 and Older with a qualifying medical condition are now. Learn when and how to make an appointment.\nHealthcare/EMS Workers, First Responders, and School Staff can be vaccinated now. You should be vaccinated at a local pharmacy that is administering the COVID vaccine:\n\nDans Fresh Market\nFresh Market\nHarmons\nMaceys\nSmiths\nWalgreens\nWalmart\n\n\nAll UtahnsWe expect vaccine to be available to all Utahns by summer 2021.\n\n\n\n\nSafety and Efficacy\n In the United States, there are many steps in place to make sure vaccines are safe and effective. These steps include clinical trials and reviews by many independent scientists, medical professionals, and public health experts. The COVID vaccine has undergone these rigorous steps, just like all vaccines; no steps were skipped or rushed. Learn more at ThisIsOurShot.com\n\n\n\nCost\n There is no cost to you to be vaccinated. If you have health insurance, vaccine providers (including Salt Lake County Health Department) may bill your insurance a vaccine administration fee. If you do not have insurance, you will not be charged.\n\n\n\nPrecautions\n It is important to continue following COVID precautions even after youve been vaccinated; it can take time after vaccination for the body to build its immune response. We will also need a large portion of our population vaccinated before we can begin phasing out face coverings, social distancing, and other infection prevention precautions—and that will take several months.\n\n\n\nMore Information\n \nFrequently Asked Questions about COVID Vaccine\nVaccine information from the Utah Department of Health.','No content','84088','7971 S 1825 W, West Jordan, UT 84088, Estados Unidos',1,NULL,'2021-02-28 07:19:24','2021-02-28 07:25:24','South Redwood Public Health Center','UT','div|order-first o